
The string "abcd" requires 5 bytes ('a', 'b', 'c', 'd', '\0'), but the array size is 4, so no null terminator is stored. This results in undefined behavior.
The array a contains the ASCII values:

'a' = 97, 'b' = 98, 'c' = 99, 'd' = 100
The pointer p is of type int* and is assigned the address of the character array. Thus, it treats the 4 bytes of the array as a single integer.
When *p is printed, it reads all 4 bytes together and interprets them as an integer value.
The actual output depends on the system architecture (endianness):
On little-endian systems (most common), it prints a large integer formed by combining the ASCII values in reverse byte order.
On big-endian systems, the value will be different.
Conclusion:
The program produces undefined and system-dependent output, as it interprets a character array as an integer using pointer casting.


#include <stdio.h>
int main()
{
   char a[4]= "abcd";
   int *p;
   p=(int *) a;
   printf("%d", *p);
   return(0);
}
